s were touched by the affair. This compulsively readable book brilliantly evokes the texture of life in 1930s Paris. It also makes an important argument about French society and culture while proposing new understandings of crime and social class in the years before World War II.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMurderzFrancezParisvCase studies. 0aWomen murdererszFrancezParisvBiography. 0aWomenzFrancezParisxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a1930s.  aclass.  acrime.  acriminology.  adetective.  aeurope.  afascism.  afemale murderers.  afeminism.  afrance.  agender and sexuality.  agender studies.  ahistory.  aimprisonment.  ainsanity defense.  ainsanity.  ainterwar paris.  alaw and society.  amadness.  amatricide.  amedia studies.  amental illness.  amurder.  amystery.  anonfiction.  aparis.  aparricide.  apatricide.  apoison.  apolitics.  apoverty.  aprison.  arespectability.  ascandal.  asensation.  asocial class.  asocial history.  atransgression.  atrials.  atrue crime.  aviolence.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026070240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094873040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948730/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY